    state/.style={triangle, shape border rotate=180, anchor=north},
    costate/.style={triangle, anchor=south},
    morphism/.style={draw, rectangle},
    over/.style={
      draw=white,
      double=black,
      % default is .4pt
      line width=1.2pt,
      double distance=.4pt,
      text=black
    },
  }

  \tikzset{ 
    % tables
    % https://tikz.net/tikz-table/
    table/.style={
        matrix of nodes,
        row sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        column sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        nodes={
            rectangle,
            draw=black,
            align=center
        },
        minimum height=1.5em,
        text depth=0.5ex,
        text height=2ex,
        nodes in empty cells,
%%
        every even row/.style={
            nodes={fill=gray!20}
        },
        column 1/.style={
            nodes={font=\bfseries}
        },
        row 1/.style={
            nodes={
                fill=black,
                text=white,
                font=\bfseries
            }
        }
    }
  }


    \begin {tikzcd}
      Rc\times  Pc\ar [d, "Rf\times  Pf"']\ar [r, "\alpha _c"] & Qc\ar [d, "Qf"]\\
      Rd\times  Pd\ar [r, "\alpha _d"'] & Qd
    \end {tikzcd}


 commutes, so that \alpha _d(Rf(r), Pf(p)) = Qf(\alpha _c(r, p)) =   \beta _c(r)_d(f, Pf(p)). Finally, since \beta  must also be natural in c,
  we can take c = d to force \beta _c(r)_d(f, p) = \alpha _d(Rf(r), p).
  Thus, this is a unique definition of \beta , and we have furthermore checked
  the required naturality conditions, so that we have demonstrated the desired
  bijection.

Analogously to the construction of the unit of an adjunction, this equivalently
means there is a map c\xrightarrow {\eta _c} Ud in C (the transpose of 1_d),
called a universal arrow to U, such that for any z\in  D, any map
x\xrightarrow {f} Uz admits a unique lift to a map d\xrightarrow {g} z in D factoring
through \eta _x:





